    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nMaybe something related to #38651 \n\nI'm using Colemak keyboard layout, which looks like:\n\n![colemak](https://colemak.com/wiki/images/7/7d/Colemak3.png)\n\nAfter upgrading to Neovim 0.12.1, I encountered a regression where combining the Shift key with any letter results in the character being sent as if it were in the QWERTY layout, even though the system is set to Colemak. But exceptionally, `Shift + ;` (Colemak: `Shift + O`) sends capital `O` correctly.\n\nThe following is the layout comparison (with `Shift` held)\n\nExpected:\n\n```\nQ   W   F   P   G   J   L   U   Y   :    {   }   |\n  A   R   S   T   D   H   N   E   I   O   \"\n   Z   X   C   V   B   K   M   <   >   ?\n```\n\nActually:\n\n```\nQ   W   E   R   T   Y   U   I   O   P   {   }   |\n  A   S   D   F   G   H   J   K   L   O   \"\n   Z   X   C   V   B   N   M   <   >   ?\n```\n\n\nThis issue appears in version 0.12.1, and does not appear in 0.11.7, and this issue does not occur in SSH with macOS Terminal.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nYou should use the Colemak keyboard layout (but maybe it can be reproduced with Dvorak, I guess), then run `nvim` in the integrated terminal of a remote session, into INSERT mode, then type Shift + letters.\n\nYou will find that you're typing as if it were QWERTY.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nWith `Shift` held, Colemak should be like this:\n\n```\nQ   W   F   P   G   J   L   U   Y   :    {   }   |\n  A   R   S   T   D   H   N   E   I   O   \"\n   Z   X   C   V   B   K   M   <   >   ?\n```\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.12.1\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno 9.2.316\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nLocal: macOS 26.4, Remote: 6.19.11-zen1-1-zen\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nvscode\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nsystem package manager (ArchLinux pacman)",
